\#\#\# Top Answer: Consider to use the [`nicefrac`](http://ctan.org/pkg/nicefrac) package. It was last updated in 1998, so it shouldn't cause *"too much trouble"*. For its drawbacks see section 1\.2 of the `xfrac` (sic!) documentation.

```
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{nicefrac}

\begin{document}

\nicefrac{1}{2}

\end{document}

```

